A group of researchers from Adelaide University in Australia conducted an examination of the data for 49 000 women in Danish National birth cohort to discover the effects of SSRI administration on the behaviour of children up to 7 years of age.
The study found that untreated depression in pregnant women was associated with an increased risk of behavioural problems.
In 210 of the children whose mothers had been treated against SSRI depression, there was no increased risk of behavioural problems compared with 231 children who were more prone to behaviour issues such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and socialization issues.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more prone to post-birth bleeding if treated with SSRI.
The analysis of medical data from 30 198 who were born at a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5%, between 11 and 16%, if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers reported.
Researchers have said that, although the study linked the use of increased risk of SSRIs, there are a large number of variables - from medicines taken during birth to the limited amount of information obtained by researchers about women's specific medical conditions - which could have had an effect on the potential for bleeding.
"It is possible that women who have taken antidepressants at an advanced stage of pregnancy were those with the most serious stage of the disease, and that is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal bleeding, not antidepressants," says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
